│ stop({"edit_points": [[1170, 1176,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding  │
│ the Issue:\nThe instcombine pass incorrectly replaces a vector udiv with      │
│ zeroinitializer for the provided IR. The source computation yields a non-zero │
│ value in the second lane when dividing by 1, but the transformed target       │
│ returns all zeros, which is wrong. This implies an over-aggressive            │
│ simplification that assumed both select branches produce the same result or   │
│ ignored a potential divide-by-zero path.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe      │
│ first transformation happens in InstCombinerImpl::visitUDiv, and it directly  │
│ replaces the udiv with zeroinitializer. The visitUDiv path first calls        │
│ simplifyUDivInst -> simplifyDiv(UDiv). Within simplifyDiv/simplifyDivRem,     │
│ there is logic to thread binops over selects and PHIs                         │
│ (threadBinOpOverSelect/threadBinOpOverPHI). For operations that may trap or   │
│ are undefined (such as division by zero), that threading can be unsafe if a   │
│ divisor may be zero on any path. InstCombine itself guards against such       │
│ speculation in foldVectorBinop using                                          │
│ isSafeToSpeculativelyExecuteWithVariableReplaced, but InstructionSimplify's   │
│ simplifyDivRem does not have such a guard before threading over               │
│ select.\n\nThe IR has a RHS that is a vector select choosing between -1 and   │
│ <0,1>. That means for some lanes the divisor may be 0, and dividing by 0 is   │
│ poison/undefined. Threading udiv over that select can cause the simplifier to │
│ attempt to simplify each arm (udiv by -1 and udiv by 0/1) and then            │
│ incorrectly conclude a uniform result (e.g., zeros), ignoring the undefined   │
│ path or collapsing poison to zero.\n\n3. Root Cause                           │
│ Analysis:\nInstructionSimplify::simplifyDivRem (used by simplifyUDivInst)     │
│ unconditionally calls threadBinOpOverSelect for all integer div/rem           │
│ opcodes:\n  if (isa<SelectInst>(Op0) || isa<SelectInst>(Op1))\n    if (Value  │
│ *V = threadBinOpOverSelect(...)) return V;\n\nThis is unsafe for div/rem when │
